\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b\fs28\lang9 Question :\b0\f1\fs22\par
 Can you take example of Linkedin website implementation and again do this analysis of what all features can be implemented on object storage, and which one (S3 or blob storage) is best for the same.\par
\par
\b\f0\fs28 Features: \b0\f1\fs22\par
1) Assign hot, cool and archive tags to accounts. \par
2) Frequency queries and append is expected whenever anyone open profile or send connect request \par
3) Account not in use for more than 3 years should be moved to archive\par
\par
\b\f0\fs28 AI Outputs: \b0\f1\fs22\par
\par
\b\f2\fs24 Claude AI : \b0\f1\fs22\par
Here's the full breakdown for a LinkedIn-style implementation:\par
\par
Feature 1 \f3\emdash  Hot/Cool/Archive tags on accounts\par
Both platforms support this, but Azure Blob wins on naming clarity:\par
Azure Blob has literal tiers called Hot, Cool, and Archive \emdash  you set them per-blob or via a lifecycle management policy. For LinkedIn, a lifecycle rule like "if lastModified > 1095 days, move to Archive" maps exactly to the 3-year requirement with zero custom code.\par
AWS S3 uses S3-Standard, S3-Standard-IA (Infrequent Access), and Glacier \emdash  conceptually identical, but the naming is indirect. You'd tag S3 objects with custom metadata to convey "hot/cool/archive" labels to your application, then use lifecycle rules to actually move them between storage classes.\par
\par
Feature 2 \emdash  Frequent reads and append (profile views, connection requests)\par
This is where the gap is most significant.\par
Azure Blob has a native Append Blob type. Every AppendBlock API call efficiently adds a segment to the end of the blob \emdash  this is exactly how event logs work. Profile view events, connection requests, messaging activity all get appended in real time. The blob stays in Hot tier while active, and a lifecycle rule transitions it to Cool after 90 days.\par
AWS S3 has no native append operation. Your options are: write a new object per event (expensive at millions of events/day), use multipart upload to simulate appending (complex orchestration), or front S3 with a service like Kinesis Data Firehose that batches writes. All of these add engineering overhead compared to Azure's first-class AppendBlock.\par
\par
Feature 3 \emdash  Archive accounts inactive for 3+ years\par
Both platforms handle this well via lifecycle policies triggered on lastModified timestamp.\par
AWS S3 offers three Glacier sub-tiers \emdash  Instant Retrieval (milliseconds, higher cost), Flexible Retrieval (3\endash 5 hours), and Deep Archive (12 hours, cheapest). This granularity is an advantage if you want to tune cost vs. recall speed precisely.\par
Azure Blob Archive rehydrates in up to 15 hours at standard priority, or under 1 hour at high-priority (billed extra). Less granular than Glacier, but the lifecycle policy syntax (daysAfterLastModificationGreaterThan: 1095) is cleaner and maps directly to the "3 year" requirement.\par
\par
Overall recommendation\par
Azure Blob Storage is the better fit for this LinkedIn scenario because two of the three features have native, first-class support: the tier labels literally match the requirement, and Append Blob eliminates the most painful engineering gap (frequent event appending).\par
The only reason to prefer AWS S3 is if your architecture already lives in AWS, or if you specifically need millisecond-level archive restores via Glacier Instant Retrieval \emdash  something Azure's Archive tier doesn't match at that speed.\par
\par
